01:25.800 --> 01:28.570
So let's meet our first
potential fooler.

01:30.730 --> 01:32.670
- I am the digital magician.

01:32.670 --> 01:36.170
That means that I combine
magic with technology.

01:36.170 --> 01:38.570
It's very important to keep up
with technology

01:38.570 --> 01:40.400
and with all the changes
that are happening,

01:40.400 --> 01:43.570
because these days you can't
do an act for 50 years.

01:43.570 --> 01:45.670
So I keep an eye
on what's coming up

01:45.670 --> 01:50.030
and what can I do to
incorporate it into my magic.

01:50.030 --> 01:51.700
I was on "Penn & Teller"
three years ago,

01:51.700 --> 01:55.500
and Penn and Teller said
"Simon, you 100% fooled us...

01:55.500 --> 01:58.170
three weeks ago when we
watched you on TV."

01:58.170 --> 01:59.900
- And that's the problem.

01:59.900 --> 02:03.030
Magicians watch
other magicians.

02:03.030 --> 02:05.630
- To fool them, you have
to be one step ahead.

02:05.630 --> 02:08.570
So this time I trained really
hard for my performance.

02:08.570 --> 02:10.500
I tried to analyze
how they think

02:10.500 --> 02:12.870
and find an appropriate
test audience.

02:12.870 --> 02:15.070
[monkey squeals]

02:15.070 --> 02:18.430
I will introduce technology
that has already started

02:18.430 --> 02:19.730
to shape our future.

02:19.730 --> 02:22.600
Penn and Teller,
it's good to see you again.

02:22.600 --> 02:25.600
[cheers and applause]

02:27.000 --> 02:29.900
- Please welcome Simon Pierro.

02:29.900 --> 02:31.630
[cheers and applause]

02:31.630 --> 02:34.770
- Thank you so much.

02:34.770 --> 02:37.070
Thank you.
It's wonderful to be back.

02:37.070 --> 02:38.270
To begin,

02:38.270 --> 02:41.530
I made a list on my phone
with celebrities.

02:41.530 --> 02:44.900
I've included Emma Stone,
famous for being an actress,

02:44.900 --> 02:47.330
Lionel Richie,
famous for being a singer,

02:47.330 --> 02:51.370
Kim Kardashian,
famous for being famous.

02:51.370 --> 02:52.730
[laughter]

02:52.730 --> 02:55.330
Sir, what's your name?
- Jake.

02:54.330 --> 02:56.100
- You look trustworthy.
- Thanks.

02:56.100 --> 02:58.070
In a second,
I'm about to give you my phone.

02:58.070 --> 02:59.230
I would like you
to add two

02:59.230 --> 03:01.400
or three more celebrities
to the list.

03:01.400 --> 03:03.500
When you've done so,
give it to someone else,

03:03.500 --> 03:04.770
and this person will do
the same

03:04.770 --> 03:06.000
and so on and so on.

03:06.000 --> 03:07.270
Okay? Thank you.

03:07.270 --> 03:09.830
You can start doing the list.

03:09.830 --> 03:12.500
In the meantime, I'll show you
a bit of my magic.

03:12.500 --> 03:15.570
Obviously...

03:15.570 --> 03:19.400
I will not use...

03:19.400 --> 03:21.500
magic wand for this.

03:21.500 --> 03:23.670
[applause]

03:23.670 --> 03:27.230
I will only use my tablet.

03:27.230 --> 03:29.070
Let's have a look
at social media.

03:29.070 --> 03:30.430
I mean,
it's a funny thing.

03:30.430 --> 03:32.430
People post
pictures of their food,

03:32.430 --> 03:34.770
but very rarely they share
pictures of their weight.

03:34.770 --> 03:36.100
[laughter]

03:36.100 --> 03:38.700
Let's find
something healthy...

03:38.700 --> 03:40.070
like this.

03:40.070 --> 03:43.370
And notice that under each
picture, it says "share,"

03:43.370 --> 03:44.870
which is a nice the thing.

03:44.870 --> 03:47.630
I always have a fork with me.
Let's give it a try.

03:47.630 --> 03:50.270
One, two, three.

03:50.270 --> 03:52.130
[crowd gasps]

03:52.130 --> 03:55.130
[applause]

03:58.030 --> 04:01.300
Some people do not share only
pictures of their food,

04:01.300 --> 04:03.270
but also of themselves.

04:03.270 --> 04:04.470
Hey, Penn,
isn't that you?

04:04.470 --> 04:06.530
- Yes, it is.
- It is. Wow. Look.

04:06.530 --> 04:10.070
I must say,
I really like your ice cream.

04:10.070 --> 04:11.930
Oh, little Penn
doesn't like that.

04:11.930 --> 04:13.370
Sorry.

04:13.370 --> 04:14.670
- [laughs]

04:14.670 --> 04:18.600
[cheers and applause]

04:18.600 --> 04:21.230
- Teller, seems we have
a picture of you as well.

04:21.230 --> 04:23.570
Oh, let's see.

04:23.570 --> 04:25.970
I'm not good, but let me help
a little bit, okay?

04:25.970 --> 04:29.570
[lighter clicks]

04:29.570 --> 04:31.730
Oh, what's in the bowl?

04:31.730 --> 04:34.200
What did you cook?
That doesn't look good.

04:35.030 --> 04:36.730
Oh.

04:36.730 --> 04:38.870
Oh, that must hurt.

04:38.870 --> 04:41.070
Well, I must say,
I did flambé...

04:41.070 --> 04:43.570
but not the food...

04:43.570 --> 04:45.370
but Teller.

04:45.370 --> 04:48.370
[laughter and applause]

04:50.870 --> 04:52.800
Okay.

04:52.800 --> 04:54.400
Let's leave it there for now.

04:54.400 --> 04:56.800
I promise you something new--

04:56.800 --> 04:59.230
a technology
that has already started

04:59.230 --> 05:01.630
to shape our future.

05:01.630 --> 05:03.200
Ladies and gentlemen,

05:03.200 --> 05:05.300
I would like
to introduce to you all

05:05.300 --> 05:06.900
my 3D printer.

05:06.900 --> 05:09.830
[applause]

05:11.470 --> 05:14.000
With this advanced
piece of technology,

05:14.000 --> 05:17.870
I can print even the most
complicated designs.

05:18.530 --> 05:20.970
So who currently has my phone?

05:20.970 --> 05:24.400
So you've all generated
random lists of celebrities.

05:24.400 --> 05:27.430
Can you tell me how many people
are on this list?

05:27.430 --> 05:29.270
- 63.
- 63.

05:29.270 --> 05:31.400
Would you be kind enough
to bring the phone

05:31.400 --> 05:32.730
and the list to Penn?

05:32.730 --> 05:35.170
Penn, give me a number
from one to 63.

05:35.170 --> 05:36.930
- Uh, 42.

05:36.930 --> 05:38.570
- 42, and let me know

05:38.570 --> 05:42.830
who is the 42nd celebrity
on the list you've created.

05:42.830 --> 05:45.870
Thank you for your help.

05:45.870 --> 05:48.670
[applause]

05:52.370 --> 05:54.330
- Marie Osmond.

05:54.330 --> 05:56.500
- Marie Osmond, great.

05:56.500 --> 05:58.470
So why not?

05:58.470 --> 06:00.000
Here's my printer.

06:00.000 --> 06:03.330
And I simply type in...

06:03.330 --> 06:06.130
Osmond.

06:06.130 --> 06:07.530
Let's print her.

06:07.530 --> 06:10.270
All I have to do,
push a button.

06:10.270 --> 06:14.000
It calibrates itself to make
a perfect Marie Osmond.

06:14.000 --> 06:16.970
What we get are
some shoes

06:16.970 --> 06:20.470
who could be
from Marie Osmond, right?

06:20.470 --> 06:22.700
Followed by a wonderful dress.

06:22.700 --> 06:27.100
I mean, even a whole torso.

06:27.100 --> 06:32.130
And now we get
a perfect replica...

06:32.130 --> 06:34.800
of Marie Osmond.

06:34.800 --> 06:36.300
[cheers and applause]

06:36.300 --> 06:38.730
[snaps fingers]
- [screams]

06:40.100 --> 06:41.530
[laughs]

06:41.530 --> 06:44.530
[cheers and applause continue]

06:47.630 --> 06:49.300
Simon!
- Marie!

06:51.000 --> 06:53.030
- Great!

06:53.030 --> 06:55.970
- You know what?

06:55.970 --> 06:57.230
- I'm really here.

06:57.230 --> 06:59.830
- There cannot be enough
Marie Osmonds in this world.

06:59.830 --> 07:01.200
- [laughs]

07:01.200 --> 07:02.530
Well, you are very sweet,

07:02.530 --> 07:05.300
but just do me a favor, Simon--
don't print a Donny.

07:05.300 --> 07:07.100
I can only handle
one of that guy.

07:07.100 --> 07:09.930
- I promise. I promise.
- [laughs]

07:09.930 --> 07:12.170
- Simon Pierro!
Marie Osmond!

07:12.170 --> 07:14.100
- Thank you.

07:14.100 --> 07:16.970
Thank you so much.

07:16.970 --> 07:20.830
- Hello.
That was amazing.

07:20.830 --> 07:22.400
Ah.

07:22.400 --> 07:24.670
So I'm guessing
you could market that,

07:24.670 --> 07:26.330
and that would be
very popular.

07:26.330 --> 07:27.830
A lot of people would buy
that machine.

07:27.830 --> 07:29.500
- I guess so, yeah.

07:29.500 --> 07:33.030
- So what kind of tricks will
be coming up next for you?

07:33.030 --> 07:35.330
- I'm reaching out
in all kinds of technology--

07:35.330 --> 07:37.600
virtual reality,
augmented reality.

07:37.600 --> 07:39.270
The great thing
about technology--

07:39.270 --> 07:41.630
it changes so fast
that the inspiration

07:41.630 --> 07:43.470
is there from one day
to the other.

07:43.470 --> 07:46.300
So you're just following up
with what happens.

07:46.300 --> 07:48.030
If you had told me
ten years ago,

07:48.030 --> 07:49.830
"Simon, you're gonna be
the iPad Magician."

07:49.830 --> 07:50.870
- Yeah.

07:50.870 --> 07:52.070
- I didn't even know
what iPad was,

07:52.070 --> 07:53.300
because it wasn't created, so.

07:53.300 --> 07:55.700
- That's amazing.
Well, look at you now.

07:55.700 --> 07:57.200
You've got double iPads.

07:57.200 --> 07:59.230
- Double iPad, three--
yeah, I made it.

07:59.230 --> 08:00.830
Next time I'll come with four.

08:00.830 --> 08:03.270
- All right, let's find out
if you fooled them.

08:03.270 --> 08:04.570
Penn, Teller.

08:04.570 --> 08:05.870
- I will tell you, Simon,

08:05.870 --> 08:08.070
we've seen a lot
of people do

08:08.070 --> 08:10.900
the film-to-life thing
with the iPad.

08:10.900 --> 08:14.730
And that is a question of just
the cleverness and timing,

08:14.730 --> 08:17.030
and everything has
to be split-second and perfect.

08:17.030 --> 08:18.800
And of all the people
we've seen do it,

08:18.800 --> 08:21.170
and it's a zillion,
you are the best at that.

08:21.170 --> 08:23.500
- Oh, thanks.
- Unbelievable.

08:23.500 --> 08:26.970
[cheers and applause]

08:26.970 --> 08:30.370
We tend to think
of the perfect timing

08:30.370 --> 08:33.770
and perfect moves being
in card magic or little stuff.

08:33.770 --> 08:39.000
But to make those iPad things
look as good as you do

08:39.000 --> 08:41.070
is just millimeters,
and timing is perfect.

08:41.070 --> 08:42.400
We just love that,

08:42.400 --> 08:44.200
but we've already covered that
and other issues.

08:44.200 --> 08:46.430
We're down to talk
about the big picture.

08:46.430 --> 08:48.170
And there's a moral issue here,
of course,

08:48.170 --> 08:49.670
is if we deal
with 3D printing,

08:49.670 --> 08:51.870
in order to keep
the morality proper,

08:51.870 --> 08:54.770
you have to kill the person
that walks into the machine

08:54.770 --> 08:56.430
when the other person
comes out.

08:56.430 --> 08:58.600
So I assume that wherever
Marie Osmond was,

08:58.600 --> 09:00.370
that one has been killed,
is that correct?

09:00.370 --> 09:02.570
- [laughs]
- Oh, no.

09:02.570 --> 09:05.430
- You know, technology
is the key to this, actually,

09:05.430 --> 09:09.100
although there are age-old
optical principles.

09:09.100 --> 09:10.900
The stuff that seems
the least important

09:10.900 --> 09:13.030
is often, as you know,
the most important.

09:13.030 --> 09:15.070
When you carry
the phone over to me,

09:15.070 --> 09:17.000
there's moments
when it's just an offbeat

09:17.000 --> 09:18.600
when stuff can happen.

09:18.600 --> 09:21.470
We also think this is
a beautiful optical principle,

09:21.470 --> 09:25.470
but we actually do not think
it is a real 3D printer.

09:25.470 --> 09:27.970
[laughter]

09:27.970 --> 09:30.530
- So did they give
you enough information?

09:30.530 --> 09:33.200
- Oh, for sure, for sure,
and the great thing about it,

09:33.200 --> 09:34.570
I would come back a third time.

09:34.570 --> 09:36.500
- Yes, please do.
Please do.

09:36.500 --> 09:38.700
You're just the best.
- Please do.

09:38.700 --> 09:41.570
Simon Pierro!
- Thank you, guys.

09:41.570 --> 09:43.670
[applause]

09:45.200 --> 09:46.470
We've got more

09:46.470 --> 09:48.300
of TV's best magic coming up.

09:48.300 --> 09:49.700
Stay close.

09:57.830 --> 10:00.830
[jazz music]

10:02.230 --> 10:03.800
- Welcome back.

10:03.800 --> 10:05.670
The road to fooling
Penn and Teller

10:05.670 --> 10:08.130
can take all kinds
of twists and turns.

10:08.130 --> 10:11.200
Let's see which fooler is
getting behind the wheel next.

10:12.970 --> 10:16.330
- My name's Nick Wallace.
I'm from Canada.

10:16.330 --> 10:20.170
Onstage I would say
I am very boyish, unassuming,

10:20.170 --> 10:24.570
but I really enjoy embracing
mystery and the unknown.

10:24.570 --> 10:27.270
You know, those dark corners
and those locked doors

10:27.270 --> 10:31.500
can be a little bit
unnerving sometimes.

10:31.500 --> 10:34.770
I created this show called
"Séance."

10:34.770 --> 10:36.730
It's sort of an interactive
ghost story.

10:36.730 --> 10:38.670
We take a random member
of the audience

10:38.670 --> 10:41.930
and use them to communicate
with the dead.

10:41.930 --> 10:45.730
The whole point was to explore
the fear of the unknown.

10:45.730 --> 10:47.670
I had a good friend once say

10:47.670 --> 10:50.300
that I was pure evil wrapped
in Mr. Rogers' sweater.

10:50.300 --> 10:51.470
[laughter]

10:51.470 --> 10:54.370
And I thought,
"I like that."

10:54.370 --> 10:57.370
[applause]

10:58.500 --> 11:03.130
- Give it up for the scary-cool
magic of Nicholas Wallace.

11:03.130 --> 11:04.700
[cheers and applause]

11:04.700 --> 11:06.470
- Thank you.
Alyson, do you want to

11:06.470 --> 11:08.630
join me over here, please?

11:08.630 --> 11:11.130
Alyson, ladies and gentlemen.
- [chuckles]

11:11.130 --> 11:14.000
- Have a seat.
- Thank you. Hi.

11:14.000 --> 11:15.570
- Nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

11:15.570 --> 11:18.200
- So, Alyson,
we're going to test your luck.

11:18.200 --> 11:19.300
- Oh.

11:19.300 --> 11:20.700
- And to do this,
we're gonna use

11:20.700 --> 11:23.330
the safest and most wholesome
things in the world--

11:23.330 --> 11:25.430
milk and cookies.
- Oh, okay.

