14:05.800 --> 14:07.800
- This is not going so well.

14:14.200 --> 14:16.530
- Don't move.
Don't move.

14:16.530 --> 14:18.300
- I have to eat another one?

14:18.300 --> 14:20.500
- Not yet.
- Aw, man.

14:24.330 --> 14:26.530
- Wait.
- I'm still--

14:26.530 --> 14:27.930
- Go!
- No.

14:27.930 --> 14:29.370
- [muffled speech]

14:32.770 --> 14:35.100
- Are you okay?
- I don't like this trick.

14:35.100 --> 14:37.000
- Okay. Okay. Okay.

14:39.800 --> 14:41.700
- I can't do it.

14:43.770 --> 14:46.000
- Don't move yet.
Don't move.

14:50.200 --> 14:52.330
Okay.

14:52.330 --> 14:54.600
Don't eat it yet.
- I can't!

14:54.600 --> 14:56.170
- I'm gonna take
your blindfold off.

14:56.170 --> 14:57.830
- Oh, God.

14:59.670 --> 15:01.270
- How's it going?

15:01.270 --> 15:03.570
- [muffled speech]
- That's all right.

15:03.570 --> 15:05.230
Before we do this--

15:05.230 --> 15:06.830
You like that cookie?
Is it good?

15:06.830 --> 15:08.700
Do you want to switch?
Is it fine?

15:08.700 --> 15:11.900
- I'm fine.
- Okay.

15:11.900 --> 15:13.670
Go.

15:14.930 --> 15:16.870
- What--

15:16.870 --> 15:18.670
what a weird trick.

15:18.670 --> 15:21.700
[laughter]

15:35.000 --> 15:37.370
- Aw, that was mean.

15:37.370 --> 15:40.370
[laughter and applause]

15:41.970 --> 15:43.730
- Your milk.

15:45.870 --> 15:48.070
Give Alyson
a round of applause.

15:48.070 --> 15:50.430
[cheers and applause]

15:50.430 --> 15:53.370
Mm, thank you.

15:53.370 --> 15:55.670
- Nicholas Wallace!

15:55.670 --> 15:57.930
[cheers and applause]

15:57.930 --> 15:59.470
- You can, uh--
- Okay, wow.

15:59.470 --> 16:00.830
Well, that was disturbing.

16:00.830 --> 16:02.230
- Do you want another--
- No.

16:02.230 --> 16:04.730
I'm not gonna take
anything from you.

16:04.730 --> 16:06.100
That was really gross.

16:06.100 --> 16:09.200
That's why you don't take food
from strangers.

16:09.200 --> 16:13.200
- I suppose, yes.
- Man, you're pretty strange.

16:13.200 --> 16:14.630
- I will take
that as a compliment.

16:14.630 --> 16:16.170
Thank you. Thank you.
- [laughs]

16:16.170 --> 16:17.230
- I mean, at the end
of the day,

16:17.230 --> 16:18.770
all we did was eat
some milk and cookies.

16:18.770 --> 16:20.270
- Yeah,
but you tried to kill me.

16:20.270 --> 16:22.070
- Well, unsuccessfully...
[laughter]

16:22.070 --> 16:23.570
I suppose, but--
- Yeah.

16:23.570 --> 16:26.300
There's some questions
I have for the producers later.

16:26.300 --> 16:28.670
- [laughs]
- I'm a little--

16:28.670 --> 16:31.570
You seem so nice,
but you're not.

16:31.570 --> 16:34.270
You're just mean.
- Well, well, I mean...

16:34.270 --> 16:36.070
- What if I had switched
the cookie?

16:36.070 --> 16:38.630
- I don't know. It would have
been a very different show...

16:38.630 --> 16:40.170
I suppose.
- Yeah.

16:40.170 --> 16:41.400
I guess so.

16:41.400 --> 16:43.630
All right, well,
let's see if your cookie magic

16:43.630 --> 16:45.800
fooled the boys.
- Okay.

16:45.800 --> 16:48.300
- Boy, we get a lot--
see, here's the problem.

16:48.300 --> 16:50.870
For those who watched
"Fool Us," other episodes,

16:50.870 --> 16:54.670
we have been fooled by
a [bleep] cookie before.

16:54.670 --> 16:56.000
[laughter]

16:56.000 --> 16:58.770
We do not want to be fooled
by a [bleep] cookie.

16:58.770 --> 17:01.270
Teller...

17:01.270 --> 17:04.430
has been sure...

17:04.430 --> 17:07.730
that it's similar
to the last time we were wrong.

17:07.730 --> 17:09.400
I'm not gonna let him do that.

17:09.400 --> 17:12.800
He thinks that--I'm not--
this is not our guess.

17:12.800 --> 17:16.099
'Cause he thinks you dumped
that cookie

17:16.099 --> 17:18.470
into the glass of milk
that you're holding there,

17:18.470 --> 17:20.430
that you dumped the cookie
with the razor blade

17:20.430 --> 17:22.730
into the glass of milk
that you're holding.

17:22.730 --> 17:25.300
And I do not think so.

17:25.300 --> 17:27.000
I do not think so.

17:27.000 --> 17:28.600
I think you can drink
that whole glass of milk,

17:28.600 --> 17:32.270
and there's not--there's not
a cookie in the bottom.

17:32.270 --> 17:34.900
[laughter]

17:37.300 --> 17:40.130
- Do it.

17:40.130 --> 17:42.600
And I'm so glad it's soy milk
right now.

17:42.600 --> 17:44.170
Ha ha!

17:44.170 --> 17:47.400
And it's warm
and not tasty.

17:47.400 --> 17:49.300
It's not even vanilla.

17:49.300 --> 17:50.700
- Exactly.

17:50.700 --> 17:54.500
And I think that
the razor blades are also real.

17:55.770 --> 18:00.200
- And I think you are
really, really, really good

18:00.200 --> 18:03.270
at sleight of hand
and all blindfolds are fake.

18:03.270 --> 18:05.830
It's not sleight of mouth,
it's not sleight of cookie,

18:05.830 --> 18:07.870
and what a great idea
for a trick.

18:07.870 --> 18:10.200
- What--was sleight
of hand involved?

18:10.200 --> 18:12.470
And were you wearing
a blindfold?

18:12.470 --> 18:14.000
- I was wearing--Oh, yes.

18:14.000 --> 18:15.970
[laughter]

18:15.970 --> 18:17.530
I was, yes.

18:17.530 --> 18:20.870
- It was sleight of hand.
You were palming it off.

18:20.870 --> 18:22.230
Was it sleight of hand?

18:22.230 --> 18:23.700
- Mm, not exac--no.

18:23.700 --> 18:25.170
- It's not sleight of hand?
- No.

18:26.800 --> 18:28.670
We're fooled
by another cookie.

18:28.670 --> 18:30.470
- [laughs]

18:30.470 --> 18:31.570
You fooled them!

18:31.570 --> 18:34.530
- We're fooled
by another cookie.

18:34.530 --> 18:37.570
That's all.
Fooled by another cookie.

18:37.570 --> 18:40.170
- Oh, my goodness.

18:40.170 --> 18:43.200
[cheers and applause]

18:45.230 --> 18:47.400
- Do you want one?
- Nicholas Wallace!

18:47.400 --> 18:50.030
- No, thank you.
[cheers and applause]

18:50.030 --> 18:52.030
- Thanks.
- Thank you.

18:52.030 --> 18:54.570
[cheers and applause continue]

18:54.570 --> 18:56.570
We've got our first fooler
of the night.

18:56.570 --> 19:00.330
Come back and see if we'll get
another after this.

19:08.670 --> 19:11.670
[jazz music]

19:12.970 --> 19:14.470
- Welcome back.

19:14.070 --> 19:17.030
Penn and Teller have barely
recovered from getting fooled,

19:17.030 --> 19:19.070
but it's already time
for the next act.

19:19.070 --> 19:20.530
Take a look.

19:22.100 --> 19:24.530
- There are, really,
only 12 notes on the piano.

19:24.530 --> 19:26.300
But there's a million
different combinations

19:26.300 --> 19:28.530
in which you can play them,
and the same goes with magic.

19:28.530 --> 19:30.070
There's only
eight effects,

19:30.070 --> 19:31.670
but, you know,
it's what you do

19:31.670 --> 19:33.330
with those eight effects.

19:33.330 --> 19:35.500
I remember back in the day,
I had nothing to say.

19:35.500 --> 19:38.600
But becoming an adult,
you have life experiences,

19:38.600 --> 19:40.070
and you have stuff
you want to say,

19:40.070 --> 19:42.230
and magic just becomes
the vehicle for that.

19:42.230 --> 19:46.100
I try to take different bits
from everything in life

19:46.100 --> 19:47.430
and put it into my magic
because, you know,

19:47.430 --> 19:49.000
that's how you connect
with the audience

19:49.000 --> 19:51.430
and make it
a really powerful experience.

19:51.430 --> 19:54.270
My brother Bruce
was two years older than me.

19:54.270 --> 19:56.130
He passed away in 2011.

19:56.130 --> 19:58.200
It put everything
into perspective.

19:58.200 --> 20:00.300
I think it really showed me
not to sweat the small stuff.

20:00.300 --> 20:02.000
We're cut from
the exact same cloth.

20:02.000 --> 20:04.000
So I know he's looking down,
proud of me,

20:04.000 --> 20:06.170
and taking this journey
and making it into a career.

20:06.170 --> 20:08.570
You know, I feel like I can see
him with his grin on his face,

20:08.570 --> 20:11.130
being like, "Nice work."

20:11.130 --> 20:15.070
[cheers and applause]

20:15.070 --> 20:18.800
- Please welcome Winnipeg's own
Darcy Oake.

20:18.800 --> 20:21.800
[cheers and applause]

20:27.170 --> 20:28.870
- Every single
person in this room

20:28.870 --> 20:31.030
can probably remember
the very first moment

20:31.030 --> 20:33.900
they ever experienced
that feeling of real magic.

20:33.900 --> 20:35.930
And for some of you,
that might be tonight.

20:35.930 --> 20:38.330
For me, it happened when
I was six years old.

20:38.330 --> 20:40.270
I was sitting around at home,
and my dad was playing

20:40.270 --> 20:41.670
with a deck of cards.

20:41.670 --> 20:43.900
Now, my dad knows zero magic.

20:43.900 --> 20:46.770
He says, "Darcy, pick a card."
I was skeptical.

20:46.770 --> 20:48.530
So I reached into the pack,
I pulled one out.

20:48.530 --> 20:50.470
I looked at it,
I put it back inside.

20:50.470 --> 20:53.000
He said, "Without looking,
I'm gonna find your card."

20:53.000 --> 20:54.630
Sure enough he closes
his eyes,

20:54.630 --> 20:56.670
spreads the cards out
face down on the table,

20:56.670 --> 20:58.630
reaches into the pack,
pulls one out,

20:58.630 --> 20:59.730
flips it over.

20:59.730 --> 21:01.400
Lo and behold,
it was my card.

21:01.400 --> 21:03.670
I was absolutely flabbergasted.

21:03.670 --> 21:05.930
Had no idea how to explain
what I just saw.

21:05.930 --> 21:08.230
Begged him for a month
to tell me how he did it.

21:08.230 --> 21:09.430
Wouldn't tell me.

21:09.430 --> 21:11.200
Finally, five weeks later,

21:11.200 --> 21:13.630
I learned it was
a complete accident.

21:13.630 --> 21:15.830
[laughter]

21:15.830 --> 21:17.870
Just so happened to work out.

21:17.870 --> 21:20.070
But that moment changed
the course of my life forever.

21:20.070 --> 21:22.230
So right now I'd like to try
to share that moment

21:22.230 --> 21:23.470
with all of you.

21:23.470 --> 21:25.630
I've got...

21:25.630 --> 21:27.070
a bottle.

21:27.070 --> 21:29.230
The bottle...
[glass tinks]

21:29.230 --> 21:31.030
Is made of glass...

21:31.030 --> 21:33.570
completely solid,
untampered with,

21:33.570 --> 21:37.130
and the cork will remain
in the mouth of the bottle.

21:37.130 --> 21:40.000
The bottle goes in the box.

21:40.000 --> 21:41.200
The box is locked

21:41.200 --> 21:44.930
and placed inside
the larger box.

21:46.900 --> 21:48.470
Now, you can stay right there,
but, Teller,

21:48.470 --> 21:50.500
if you can me a favor and hold
on to the box for me.

21:50.500 --> 21:52.900
We'll just rest it right
on your lap.

21:52.900 --> 21:54.100
Right here,
if that's all right.

21:54.100 --> 21:55.400
Thank you very much.

21:55.400 --> 21:56.500
Penn.
- Yes, sir.

21:56.500 --> 21:58.730
- We have a deck of cards
right here.

21:58.730 --> 22:01.530
We will remove the jokers
from the pack.

22:01.530 --> 22:03.870
They'll sit right there.
Thank you very much.

22:03.870 --> 22:05.770
You can see that all
of the cards

22:05.770 --> 22:08.570
are, in fact, different--
no two are the same.

22:08.570 --> 22:10.870
What I'm gonna do in one second
is I'm gonna hand you the deck.

22:10.870 --> 22:12.970
And behind your back,
I want you to take

22:12.970 --> 22:15.200
one card out from the middle,

22:15.200 --> 22:17.230
flip it over,
put it face up on top,

22:17.230 --> 22:18.500
and then cut it into the pack.

22:18.500 --> 22:19.730
Sound good?
- Okay.

22:19.730 --> 22:22.030
- So behind your back,
take out one card,

22:22.030 --> 22:24.100
put it face up on top,
cut it into the deck.

22:24.100 --> 22:26.800
So, that way, nobody knows
what card you've selected.

22:26.800 --> 22:28.870
- So I reach anywhere I want
in the middle?

22:28.870 --> 22:30.100
- Anywhere in the middle,
pull it out--

22:30.100 --> 22:32.130
- Take out one card,
put it face up on top, right?

22:32.130 --> 22:34.130
- Don't look, Teller,
if you don't mind. Thank you.

22:34.130 --> 22:36.230
- And then I'm going to cut it
somewhere in the middle.

22:36.230 --> 22:37.570
- Exactly.

22:37.570 --> 22:39.470
- I think I have followed
all the directions properly.

22:39.470 --> 22:41.070
And there is the deck.
- I hope so. Perfect.

22:41.070 --> 22:43.630
- There should be one card
face up in the deck there.

22:43.630 --> 22:45.300
- Excellent.
We'll have a look here.

22:45.300 --> 22:47.470
If we go through, we can see--
- Now it's gonna be face down.

22:47.470 --> 22:49.330
- We can see one card
is face down,

22:49.330 --> 22:51.330
one card only.

22:51.330 --> 22:54.070
You have selected
the five of hearts.

22:54.070 --> 22:56.000
Nice choice, Penn.

22:56.000 --> 23:00.370
Watch very closely 'cause we
will do this very, very slowly.

23:00.370 --> 23:01.630
Your five of hearts--

23:01.630 --> 23:03.700
you could have selected
any card in the pack.

23:03.700 --> 23:06.370
We will take one of the jokers.

23:06.370 --> 23:09.770
And all we're gonna do
is sandwich it..

23:09.770 --> 23:12.470
right between...

23:12.470 --> 23:13.870
the jokers.

23:13.870 --> 23:17.100
Watch closely, 'cause this
will happen very quickly.

23:17.100 --> 23:18.600
You could have selected
any card in the deck.

23:18.600 --> 23:21.130
You chose the five of hearts,
which is now sandwiched

23:21.130 --> 23:23.270
between the two jokers.

23:23.270 --> 23:24.500
Here we go, watch.

23:24.500 --> 23:26.530
Give it a little shake,

23:26.530 --> 23:28.930
and it vanishes.

23:28.930 --> 23:30.270
Gone.

23:30.270 --> 23:33.270
[applause]

23:35.570 --> 23:37.770
The hands...

23:37.770 --> 23:39.600
are empty.

23:39.600 --> 23:41.700
Inside this box--
check it out--

23:41.700 --> 23:44.430
is the other box.

23:44.430 --> 23:46.700
Inside this box,

23:46.700 --> 23:49.200
have a look inside.

23:49.200 --> 23:53.130
- Whoa.
[audience gasps]

23:53.130 --> 23:55.700
[cheers and applause]

23:59.070 --> 24:01.270
- Darcy Oake!

24:01.270 --> 24:03.530
[cheers and applause]

24:03.530 --> 24:06.200
- Thank you.
- That was awesome.

24:06.200 --> 24:07.900
Oh, my goodness,
and you did it

24:07.900 --> 24:09.500
right in Teller's lap.

24:09.500 --> 24:12.230
- Risky business.
- Yeah. That's so cool.

24:12.230 --> 24:13.800
How long have
you been into magic?

24:13.800 --> 24:14.770
- Since I was a kid.

24:14.770 --> 24:15.900
Since I was about six
or seven years old.

24:15.900 --> 24:17.430
And that's actually
a true story.

24:17.430 --> 24:19.000
- Oh, since your dad, yes.
- Yeah. Yeah.

24:19.000 --> 24:22.230
Actually, I went
to university for one year

24:22.230 --> 24:24.600
after high school and,
obviously,

24:24.600 --> 24:26.600
was failing everything
'cause I was so focused

24:26.600 --> 24:28.470
on performing
and learning magic.

24:28.470 --> 24:30.530
And I eventually learned
that if you had

24:30.530 --> 24:33.330
unpaid parking tickets,
the university

24:33.330 --> 24:35.070
wouldn't send your transcripts
to your parents.

24:35.070 --> 24:36.670
So I racked up all these
parking tickets,

24:36.670 --> 24:38.400
and they never knew
that I failed.

24:38.400 --> 24:40.200
[laughter]
It was perfect.

24:40.200 --> 24:43.370
- Oh, man, you just gave
some really bad advice

24:43.370 --> 24:45.070
to so many people.
- Yeah, yeah, I mean--

24:45.070 --> 24:46.670
[laughter]

24:46.670 --> 24:48.230
- And do you work all the time?

24:48.230 --> 24:50.370
- Yeah, I mean,
I've been pretty consistently

24:50.370 --> 24:51.630
on the road
for the past little bit.

24:51.630 --> 24:53.030
And, like, all I've
ever wanted to do is

24:53.030 --> 24:55.070
turn my passion into--
into a career.

24:55.070 --> 24:57.730
One of the highlights, I guess,
of my career so far--

24:57.730 --> 25:00.430
I got to do a show for
the Queen of England

25:00.430 --> 25:01.500
on her 90th birthday.

25:01.500 --> 25:03.100
- Wow!
- Yeah, in Windsor Castle.

25:03.100 --> 25:05.070
So that was--Yeah, yeah.
- That's incredible.

25:05.070 --> 25:06.600
- Oh, a little applause
for that.

25:06.600 --> 25:09.170
- Yeah.
That's impressive.

25:09.170 --> 25:10.870
- It was so surreal.
It was crazy.

25:10.870 --> 25:13.200
both: Yeah.
- So what's your dream gig?

25:13.200 --> 25:15.070
Or have you already done it?

25:15.070 --> 25:17.230
- Well, it's tough to say,
but I think, you know,

25:17.230 --> 25:18.600
for me, it's just
to keep performing

25:18.600 --> 25:21.270
and just being able
to do it as a job, you know?

25:21.270 --> 25:23.330
'Cause when you turn
your passion into a career,

25:23.330 --> 25:25.070
you don't work a day
in your life, right?

25:25.070 --> 25:27.400
- Exactly.
Yeah, all right.

25:27.400 --> 25:29.330
Well, let's--let's see
if the boys

25:29.330 --> 25:31.670
have figured it out.
- Let's do it.

25:31.670 --> 25:34.630
- You know, it's really
charming when we have people on

25:34.630 --> 25:38.170
that don't do magic full-time,
all the time,

25:38.170 --> 25:40.370
but it's also wonderful
to see a real pro.

25:40.370 --> 25:42.770
You just have real style,
real grace,

25:42.770 --> 25:45.530
and also,
you brought it down to us.

25:45.530 --> 25:47.700
You know, a lot of guys
try to stay as far away

25:47.700 --> 25:49.030
from us as they can.

25:49.030 --> 25:50.370
They take a little deck
of cards

25:50.370 --> 25:52.530
and say, "Penn and Teller,
I'll be at the other end

25:52.530 --> 25:54.330
"of the football field
if you need me.

25:54.330 --> 25:55.700
Watch these card moves."

25:55.700 --> 25:58.730
You brought it right
down into our laps.

25:58.730 --> 26:01.600
The selection
that I did was fabulous.

26:01.600 --> 26:04.970
That's a really, really smart,
clever way to do that,

26:04.970 --> 26:07.670
even though it
doesn't adhere

26:07.670 --> 26:10.500
to strict card table protocol.

26:10.500 --> 26:13.300
It still seems like
a completely free choice.

26:13.300 --> 26:14.670
It was great that way.

26:14.670 --> 26:18.370
Doing the joker thing,
the acrobatic thing

26:18.370 --> 26:20.900
right in Teller's face
was great.

26:20.900 --> 26:23.400
And then we also know

26:23.400 --> 26:27.470
that we've read all
the books of Robert Hartman.

26:27.470 --> 26:29.500
Is that a magic word to you
right there?

26:29.500 --> 26:31.230
- Exactly.

26:31.230 --> 26:33.070
- So you deserve a cigar
for doing a great show.

26:33.070 --> 26:35.200
- Oh, thank you.
- Great show.

26:35.200 --> 26:36.900
- Does that mean
they figured it out?

26:36.900 --> 26:39.830
- It does. Of course. Exactly.
- Well, thank you.

26:39.830 --> 26:41.570
- Thank you.
- Darcy Oake!

26:41.570 --> 26:42.930
- Thank you so much.
- Thank you.

26:42.930 --> 26:44.870
- Thank you, guys.
Thank you.

26:44.870 --> 26:47.100
[cheers and applause]

26:47.100 --> 26:50.030
- We'll be right back
with more outrageous magic,

26:50.030 --> 26:52.830
including a trick by the best
in the business--

26:52.830 --> 26:54.370
Penn and Teller!

27:02.770 --> 27:05.770
[jazz music]

27:06.870 --> 27:08.830
- Welcome back to "Fool Us."

27:08.830 --> 27:11.000
Sure, we search the world
for the best magic,

27:11.000 --> 27:12.870
but we also find
great performers

27:12.870 --> 27:14.200
right in our backyard.

27:14.200 --> 27:16.000
Check out this next act.

27:17.700 --> 27:20.570
- When I first moved
to Las Vegas...

27:20.570 --> 27:22.100
it was a big risk.

27:22.100 --> 27:23.730
I was nervous.
I didn't know anybody.

27:23.730 --> 27:26.070
And I ran into
this great magician.

27:26.070 --> 27:28.100
And I said,
"Hey, you're Johnny Thompson."

27:28.100 --> 27:29.430
And he turned to me,
and he said,

27:29.430 --> 27:30.930
"Oh, you must be a magician."

27:30.930 --> 27:32.770
I showed him something
that impressed him.

27:32.770 --> 27:35.030
It confirmed that I made
the right decision

27:35.030 --> 27:36.830
moving to Las Vegas.

27:38.400 --> 27:41.300
Jeet Kune Do, Bruce Lee's
martial arts discipline,

27:41.300 --> 27:44.000
utilizing universal concepts,
such as fluidity,

27:44.000 --> 27:46.730
completely changed
my coin magic.

27:46.730 --> 27:49.330
Cards and coins, uh,
they can have a bad rap.

27:49.330 --> 27:50.670
A lot of the great moves

27:50.670 --> 27:52.370
were invented by charlatans
and the cheats

27:52.370 --> 27:54.070
who were trying to cheat
each other at cards.

27:54.070 --> 27:57.770
I don't let that affect
the way my magic has to be.

27:57.770 --> 28:00.070
I create my own stuff.

